## Conventions Established Across Posts #1 & #2

These must be followed exactly in Post #3:

**TDD workflow:** Always write the spec first (Red), implement to make it pass (Green), then refactor. Never write implementation before the spec.

**Phase numbering:** Each post uses sequential phases (Phase 1, Phase 2, ...). Post #3 starts at Phase 1 again.

**Spec structure — model specs:**
- `describe "database columns"` — `have_db_column` matchers
- `describe "validations"` — `shoulda-matchers` one-liners + context blocks for edge cases
- `describe "associations"` — `belong_to`, `have_many` matchers
- `describe "#method_name"` — instance method behaviour

**Spec structure — feature specs:**
- One file per CRUD action in `spec/features/<resource>/`
- `create_`, `list_`, `show_`, `edit_`, `delete_` prefixes
- All factory records pin every name/slug-contributing field explicitly (no random middle names etc.)
- `record.reload` before asserting on paths after slug-changing updates

**`friendly_id`:** Always use `use: [:slugged, :history]`. Always override `should_generate_new_friendly_id?`. For virtual attribute slugs (like `full_name`), check the underlying real columns in `should_generate_new_friendly_id?`. For real column slugs (like `title`), use `column_changed?` directly.

**Numericality validations:** Never use `in: range` — use explicit `greater_than_or_equal_to:` and `less_than_or_equal_to:` so `shoulda-matchers` error messages match.

**Factories:** Never use Rails generator defaults (`"MyString"`, `1`). Never set `slug` manually. Use `sequence(:title)` for uniqueness. Cap `day` at 28 to avoid invalid date construction.

**Generator cleanup:** Always delete `spec/requests/<resource>_spec.rb` and `spec/views/<resource>/` stubs after running the controller generator.

**Views:** Always implement all five files: `index`, `show`, `new`, `edit`, `_form`. The `_form` partial renders validation errors. The `show` view includes a `button_to "Delete ..."` with `method: :delete`.

**`rails generate model` columns:** Never use `field:type:null:false` syntax — the generator rejects it. Generate plain columns, then add `null: false` manually in the migration.

**Commit message format (enforced by git hook):**
```
<App>:  <type>:  <description min 10 chars>
```
Allowed apps: `Main`, `Event_Tracker`, `Blog_Posts`, `Recipes`, `Photo_Album`
Allowed types: `feat`, `fix`, `refactor`, `test`, `chore`, `docs`, `style`, `perf`, `build`, `revert`

Example: `Event_Tracker:  feat:  Add EventType model with TDD`

**Git workflow:**
1. Create feature branch: `git checkout -b feature/<name>`
2. Do all work on the branch
3. Commit with correctly formatted message (hook validates on commit)
4. `git merge main` on the feature branch before pushing
5. `git push origin feature/<name>` (pre-push hook re-validates all commit messages)
6. Open PR on GitHub — CI runs `ci.yml` and `commit-lint.yml`
7. Merge on GitHub only — never merge locally into `main`
8. `git checkout main && git pull && git branch -d feature/<name>`

**Test data:** Metallica. Keep using Metallica members as `Person` seed data and Metallica-related data for any new seed records.

